Rating: 0
In fact, leeks are botanologically a member of the onion family, so no, substituting them for onions isn't weird at all. You might also want to experiment with different kinds of onions -- shallots, for instance, also have a milder, more delicate flavor than regular onions and might work for you. As regards the issue of sliced bread: having traveled extensively all over Italy practically every year since 1979 and even having lived there for a few months once, I have to agree with Phil that no self-respecting Italian would ever use sliced bread. The issue is not in the slicing, it is that pre-sliced bread is full of all kinds of additives and preservatives that keep it fresh even though it's exposed to the air, and they affect the flavor. And Peggy, really, why all the sarcasm? I am amazed at the number of people on this site who are nasty to others. We all come from different backgrounds, okay? I thought the point of writing reviews was to *help*. I, for one, thoroughly enjoy the diversity of viewpoints on this site. Let's not kill it. Say whatever it is that you want to say, just don't be nasty about it.

